snippet.title: GQ Magazine Writer Responds To Amber Rose's Strong Criticism | Sway's Universe
snippet.description:
Yesterday, Amber Rose hit the Gram to express her disappointment in GQ‚Äôs choice of words in their article about her. Here‚Äôs what the magazine printed:

‚ÄúAmber Rose wrote the book on it. No, seriously: Kanye‚Äôs infamous ex, Wiz Khalifa‚Äôs baby mama, America‚Äôs toughest bald babe since Sigourney Weaver in Alien 3, is about to publish a book of life lessons called How to Be a Bad Bitch. Like Amber herself, it‚Äôs all heart. Unlike Amber, it‚Äôs not that thick! The teen stripper turned megalomaniac muse spoke to Carrie Battan about her beautiful dark twisted journey to the top.‚Äù

Ms. Rose didn‚Äôt find it so amusing. She screenshot the piece, posted on her IG, and gave her 2 cents.

‚ÄúReally @gq??? I‚Äôm so much more then Kanye‚Äôs Ex or Wiz‚Äôs baby‚Äôs mama. Damn, why the (expletive) did u guys reach out to me for this article and photoshoot? To dumb me down? I talked about feminism and my Slutwalk‚Ä¶ Wtf nice title smh I expected so much more from u guys and I‚Äôm so disappointed. I was so excited to be featured in GQ not realizing I was shooting for a tabloid. My slutwalk was for ignorant (expletive) like this. Oh ‚ÄúHer beautiful dark twisted journey to the top‚Äù? Nice pun. Negative af. Thx for nothing.‚Äù

Why did GQ choose to call her Wiz‚Äôs ‚Äúbaby mama‚Äù instead of ‚Äúex-wife?‚Äù Well, we spoke to the writer of the story, Carrie Baton to get her thoughts.

‚ÄúIf you notice, she cut out the title of the piece, which was ‚ÄòHow to Be a Bad Bitch,‚Äô which is the title of her book. Which is kind of the highest praise we could have given her.‚Äù

Carrie elaborates with her intention on the piece.

‚ÄúMy goal was to find a way to explain to people the challenges that she‚Äôs facing while she‚Äôs sort of transitioning in these two fazes of her life. and sort of what her feminism stand point is and how it ties into what people know her as.‚Äù

news,gossip,rumors,rap,exposed,entertainment,the truth,instagram,snapchat,twitter,jtnews,jay z,4:44,gucci mane,drama,meek mill movie,breaking news,meek mill drake,drake meek mill,nicki minaj meek mill,meek mill diss nicki minaj,Jay-Z Is Losing Out on Millions of Dollars by Keeping ‚Äò4:44‚Äô Off Spotify Read More: Jay-Z Is Losing,jayz z 444,444,jay z diss drake,jay z future,jay z beef

JAY-Z is missing out on a huge chunk of cash by refusing to allow Spotify stream his latest album, 4:44. How much? Hov is forfeiting weekly checks of close to a million dollars, according to Billboard.
The projected number is based on ‚Äúshare of the market and the average rate paid per song stream.‚Äù However, others project that the payout would be closer to $250,000 if he put the LP on Spotify‚Äôs paid tier for seven days. Either way, that‚Äôs a big sum to be leaving on the table.
Jigga initially released the album exclusively through his streaming service, Tidal and telecommunications giant Sprint. He later released the project through iTunes and Apple Music, but has yet to give Spotify the rights to the LP. There may be more to Spotify not getting the record than just not wanting to give his work to a rival company.
‚Äú[JAY-Z] would choose to frame this as potentially saying all music should be paid for and positioning his release against Spotify‚Äôs free tier,‚Äù said MIDiA Research analyst Zach Fuller. ‚ÄúWhether or not that argument stands up depends on who you speak to. You can commend Spotify for engendering this audience that previously would be downloading the music illegally.‚Äù
Despite not being on Spotify, 4:44 has been one of the top releases of 2017, sales wise.
Jay is on pace to drop a video for all the songs on the project, after releasing visuals every week since the album has been out. The most recent treatment for ‚ÄúKill Jay Z‚Äù came out yesterday (July 21).

snippet.description:
In Episode 4 of Prolific Roots we get the opportunity to sit down with Amber Aiono Johnson. Amber is currently a Director of Sales at Divvy. A Utah based startup that is expected to become the next billion dollar unicorn.

Amber is a huge Kobe Bryant fan and in her story she shares a bit about how she used that Mamba Mentality to improve her skills as a Saleswoman so much that she eventually became a Director of Sales, started and sold a company, and then became a Director of Sales again at Divvy (despite dropping out of college).

snippet.description:
On today‚Äôs episode of The SHAIR Podcast Amber Leone Murphy the founder of ‚ÄúCan‚Äôt Keep a Sober Girl Down‚Äù and the author of ‚ÄúCrushing Codependency‚Äù shares with us her incredible battle with alcoholism.  Amber now 9 years sober, started drinking at 8 years old sneaking sips of beer from left over beer cans at family parties. For over 10 years, Amber alcoholism would gradually get worse and worse: drinking on the job, public intoxication, arrested for a DUI, and sleeping in her car. snippet.title: Amber Rose SLAMS Haters Who Shamed Son for Liking Taylor Swift
snippet.description:
More Celebrity News ‚ñ∫‚ñ∫ http://bit.ly/SubClevverNews

Nothing. The answer is nothing, and Amber Rose is here to remind you of that, as she should- since a few too many people on the internet found an issue with an adorable video of Amber‚Äôs son gushing over T-Swift concert tickets. The back story here is that Amber‚Äôs 5 year old son really loves Taylor Swift, so when Taylor sent tickets to Amber, of course she had to get his reaction on camera. But she obviously didn‚Äôt expect any backlash, including horrible comments about her son‚Äôs sexuality, for posting the video online. She quickly took to her Instagram, and in a series of stories, she shut those haters right down. 
She said QUOTE: "Shout-out to all the hyper-masculine men and ignorant dumb-ass women that will call a 5-year-old gay for liking Taylor Swift. This is why young kids kill themselves. And this is also why our society is so f-cked up. Liking a certain type of music will not make you 'pick' your sexuality, you dumb f-cks."P.S. My son just got accepted into the most prestigious private school in Los Angeles because he's smart as f-ck and creative as f-ck like his parents. We allow him to be himself. He can listen to whatever music he likes, he can like whatever color he wants and we let him be passionate about whatever his little heart desires."
And that wasn‚Äôt powerful enough, Amber continued saying QUOTE 
Let's do better for the next generation, people. Grow the f-ck up and teach your kids to love and not hate. P.S.S. Regardless if he's gay or straight, when he gets older, he will be around the most amazing, loving people that will support him no matter what."
And if THAT wasn‚Äôt powerful enough, she ended her rant saying QUOTE ‚ÄúHe also has more money in his bank account than any of you trolls could even imagine.‚Äù
These are my favorite kind of rants, tbh, as a mother, and just as a human. 
But now it‚Äôs time for you to weigh in with your thoughts on Amber‚Äôs clap back, so drop it down in the comments below, and then click right here to see the adorable moment Amber‚Äôs son realized he was going to the Taylor Swift concert. Thanks so much for hanging out with me here on Clevver News, I‚Äôm Sinead de Vries, and I‚Äôll see you guys next time.

Let's do better for the next generation, people. Grow the f-ck up and teach your kids to love and not hate. P.S.S. Regardless if he's gay or straight, when he gets older, he will be around the most amazing, loving people that will support him no matter what."
And if THAT wasn‚Äôt powerful enough, she ended her rant saying QUOTE ‚ÄúHe also has more money in his bank account than any of you trolls could even imagine.‚Äù
These are my favorite kind of rants, tbh, as a mother, and just as a human. 
But now it‚Äôs time for you to weigh in with your thoughts on Amber‚Äôs clap back, so drop it down in the comments below, and then click right here to see the adorable moment Amber‚Äôs son realized he was going to the Taylor Swift concert. Thanks so much for hanging out with me here on Clevver News, I‚Äôm Sinead de Vries, and I‚Äôll see you guys next time.

snippet.title: Ep 258: Shiny Object Syndrome with Amber Hawley
snippet.description:
Joining me today is Amber Hawley. Amber is a licensed therapist, multiple biz owner and former tech industry dropout. She hosts the Easily Distracted Entrepreneur podcast, where she supports ADHD {and ADHD-ish} business owners to overcome what she calls‚Äúshiny object syndrome.‚Äù 
Amber & her husband have both struggled with ADHD and we speak candidly about strategies for overcoming distractions in both home and business.
During our conversation Amber shares:
How she craves organization as a way to reclaim control 
The struggle to NOT do all the things (and strategies on how to work through it)
The importance of delegating (and how to do it)
If you or someone you love struggles with ADHD, this is a must-listen episode.  
Amber reminds us that with the right strategies, anyone can live an organized life. 
Make sure to check out the links we talked about below in our show notes, including her Free Shiny Object Checklist.  @ed

snippet.title: Too True: The Poetry of Elizabeth Bachinsky, Marita Dachsel, Amber Dawn and Jennica Harper
snippet.description:
November 15, 2013

Acclaimed BC poets, Elizabeth Bachinsky, Marita Dachsel, Amber Dawn, and Jennica Harper read from their most recent books and engage in a discussion about the nature of truth in poetry, mining biography and autobiography in their works, and whether or not it is possible to be too true.

Elizabeth Bachinsky is the author of five collections of poetry: Curio, Home of Sudden Service, God of Missed Connections, I Don‚Äôt Feel so Good, and The Hottest Summer in Recorded History. Her poetry has been nominated for awards including the Pat Lowther Award, The Kobzar Literary Award, The George Ryga Award for Social Awareness in Literature, the Governor General's Award for Poetry and the Bronwen Wallace Award, and has appeared in literary journals, anthologies and on film around the world. She was born in Regina, raised in Prince George and Maple Ridge B.C., and now lives in Vancouver where she is an instructor of creative writing and the Editor of EVENT magazine.

Marita Dachsel is the author of Glossolalia , Eliza Roxcy Snow, and All Things Said & Done. Her poetry has been shortlisted for the Robert Kroetsch Award for Innovative Poetry and the ReLit Prize and has appeared in many literary journals and anthologies, including Best Canadian Poetry in English, 2011. Her play Initiation Trilogy was produced by Electric Company Theatre, was featured at the 2012 Vancouver International Writers Fest, and was nominated for the Jessie Richardson Award for Outstanding New Script. She is the Artist in Residence at UVic‚Äôs Centre for Studies in Religion and Society. After many years in Vancouver and Edmonton, she and her family now live in Victoria.

Amber Dawn is a writer from Vancouver, Canada. Author of Lambda Award-winning novel Sub Rosa and editor of the anthologies Fist of the Spider Women: Fear and Queer Desire and With A Rough Tongue: Femmes Write Porn. Until August 2012, she was director of programming for the Vancouver Queer Film Festival. Amber Dawn was 2012 winner of the Writers‚Äô Trust of Canada Dayne Ogilvie Prize for LGBT writers. She currently teaches Speculative Fiction writing at Douglas College.

Jennica Harper‚Äôs most recent book of poetry is Wood. Her previous books are What It Feels Like for a Girl and The Octopus and Other Poems, and she has a poem forthcoming in the anthology I Found It at the Movies. Her long poem ‚ÄúLiner Notes‚Äù won a Silver National Magazine Award, and her work has twice been selected for Vancouver‚Äôs Poetry in Transit program. Jennica is also a film and TV writer, and most recently wrote on YTV‚Äôs teen comedy Mr. Young.

Story https://nypost.com/2019/10/07/slain-witness-joshua-brown-was-expected-to-testify-in-lawsuit-against-dallas-police/

Ten days after he testified in the murder trial of a former Dallas police officer #Amberguyger key witness #JoshuaBrown was gunned down at his apartment complex, according to the Dallas County medical examiner and Kimberlee Leach, spokesperson for Dallas County District Attorney John Creuzot. 

Story https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/05/us/botham-jean-neighbor-killed/index.html

Torain was also a contracted writer for the SOURCE Magazine and hosted the Beat Suite on MTV. His popular radio show Star & Buc Wild is often given credit for inspiring todays podcast generation. snippet.title: Amber L. Lassiter Appears on The Reading Circle with Marc Medley
snippet.description:
Amber Lynnette Lassiter has a Masters of Arts and Teaching in Education, and a Masters of Arts in Reading. She certified as an Elementary Teacher and Reading Specialist. Amber has been recognized for her leadership skills and helping to transform underperforming schools while increasing the graduation and student retention rates of college students.

She has served as a classroom teacher and reading specialist for over thirteen years. She has also worked as an adjunct instructor teaching Developmental Reading courses, English as a Second Language course, served as the Director of the Center for Academic Success at Berkeley College, and facilitated workshop at several conferences addressing topics such as Strategies to Simplify the Complexities of Biology, and Conquering Test Taking Anxiety.

She is a member of the National Teacher Sorority Phi Delta Kappa Incorporated and is obtaining an Educational Specialist degree from Seton Hall University.

snippet.title: Developing your BS detector | Amber Hunt | TEDxXavierUniversity
snippet.description:
Amber, an investigative journalist, discusses the best ways to distinguish between truths and lies in everyday life. 

As a journalist, Amber Hunt has spent much of her career fine-tuning her BS detector in hopes of figuring out the truth to tell readers. She's been known to sanctimoniously grill sources she's caught in a lie how they sleep at night. But she's a also a big believer in some truths being more subjective than others, which can make her job incredibly complicated at times. Hunt is a New York Times bestselling author and nationally award-winning journalist who works as an investigative reporter with the Cincinnati Enquirer. She previously covered crime for the Detroit Free Press and oversaw reporters in North and South Dakota as a news editor for The Associated Press. Hunt has written three true-crime books, as well as the bestselling biography The Kennedy Wives: Triumph and Tragedy in America's Most Public Family. Hunt is a past Knight-Wallace Fellow at the University of Michigan, and she teaches multimedia journalism at the University of Cincinnati. 

This talk was given at a TEDx event using the TED conference format but independently organized by a local community. Learn more at http://ted.com/tedx

snippet.title: Plaid land chapter 1 a letter from Amber
snippet.description:
Intro

                                                                   
I've been to hell. Not literally. But if you call Plaidson New Jersey hell, you get where I'm coming from. You see in Plaidson you're either on 1 of the 2 sides.

A. rich
Or
B. poor

And you see Since I, Amber Rivera am a citizen of Plaidson... I guess ill give you some play by play or in others words advise. 

Point A: watch out for rich people...yes I'm poor.

Point B: when a rich boy pulls you in a closet you might as well yell "rape!!!".

Point C: ... I've got nothing

But as we conclude today's lesson we can say you're ready for Plaidson new jersey. See you there.

Love,

         Amber Rivera
  

Chapter 1

Nicole's POv

Living is something we only realize is beautiful until someone loses its possession. Last year my mother died. And I don't know my father. Don't get me wrong my life's not that out of the ordinary my mother wasn't brutally murdered, even thou that is terrible, she was sick with cancer.

That is why I'm here in Plaidson, New Jersey to live with my cousin Amber and her family. The funny thing is right now I don't know what to feel. I mean I feel grateful, because I had to sleep in an orphanage until now, but wow. You see dear friend I haven't heard the best things about Plaidson. And I'm guessing you got the whole point speech from Amber. Wow she gave it in letter form! Are you serious? Wow!

"Nicole time for school!" 

That must be amber. Later.

"Coming," I screeched running down the stairs.

"Whoa Buba!" I was shocked to see Amber standing there in a pair of daisy dukes.

"Are those the pants I let you borrow?" Amber began to pout as if she was trying to forget.

"I know they are hideous. But they are all I have left all your other clothes are packed away and mine are in the wash." She sighed while putting on a pair of dorky glasses and retainer. 

"What are you doing?" I asked concerned.

"Getting ready for school," I gave her a look. "Ok look I don't want to get raped or anything so I dress like a dork."

What the hell was wrong with this school? I would not let amber hide her beauty. I took off the glasses and broke them in half after that I took out her retainer and crushed it. She gasped.

"If they touch you ill kick their ass!" I gave her a reassuring smile she nodded.



On the other side of town on the front stairs of school

Nick's pov


"Why are we here?" Zac asked in his pathetic tone.

I sighed

"To drink beer and think a little, stupid ass!" I exclaimed.

"We all know you need time to think for once," Joey murmured loud enough for us all to hear.

We all laughed. That's why Joey is my best friend.

snippet.localized.title: Plaid land chapter 1 a letter from Amber
snippet.localized.description:
Intro

                                                                   
I've been to hell. Not literally. But if you call Plaidson New Jersey hell, you get where I'm coming from. You see in Plaidson you're either on 1 of the 2 sides.

A. rich
Or
B. poor

And you see Since I, Amber Rivera am a citizen of Plaidson... I guess ill give you some play by play or in others words advise. 

Point A: watch out for rich people...yes I'm poor.

Point B: when a rich boy pulls you in a closet you might as well yell "rape!!!".

Point C: ... I've got nothing

But as we conclude today's lesson we can say you're ready for Plaidson new jersey. See you there.

Love,

         Amber Rivera
  

Chapter 1

Nicole's POv

Living is something we only realize is beautiful until someone loses its possession. Last year my mother died. And I don't know my father. Don't get me wrong my life's not that out of the ordinary my mother wasn't brutally murdered, even thou that is terrible, she was sick with cancer.

That is why I'm here in Plaidson, New Jersey to live with my cousin Amber and her family. The funny thing is right now I don't know what to feel. I mean I feel grateful, because I had to sleep in an orphanage until now, but wow. You see dear friend I haven't heard the best things about Plaidson. And I'm guessing you got the whole point speech from Amber. Wow she gave it in letter form! Are you serious? Wow!

"Nicole time for school!" 

That must be amber. Later.

"Coming," I screeched running down the stairs.

"Whoa Buba!" I was shocked to see Amber standing there in a pair of daisy dukes.

"Are those the pants I let you borrow?" Amber began to pout as if she was trying to forget.

"I know they are hideous. But they are all I have left all your other clothes are packed away and mine are in the wash." She sighed while putting on a pair of dorky glasses and retainer. 

"What are you doing?" I asked concerned.

"Getting ready for school," I gave her a look. "Ok look I don't want to get raped or anything so I dress like a dork."

What the hell was wrong with this school? I would not let amber hide her beauty. I took off the glasses and broke them in half after that I took out her retainer and crushed it. She gasped.

"If they touch you ill kick their ass!" I gave her a reassuring smile she nodded.



On the other side of town on the front stairs of school

Nick's pov


"Why are we here?" Zac asked in his pathetic tone.

I sighed

"To drink beer and think a little, stupid ass!" I exclaimed.

And at that same time Ryan walked up with Jessie Joey's little brother, both of them with crazy sex hair.

"Sup guys." Jessie said lazily.

Joey gave him a look that meant 'we are talking later'

snippet.title: Autumn Is Amber: Georgia Revisited with Gvantsa Abuladze & Noel Brockett
snippet.description:
Autumn Is Amber: Georgia Revisited with Gvantsa Abuladze & Noel Brockett

Gvantsa Abuladze and her sister Baia make some of Imereti's finest wines across all genres, white, orange, pink, red, and sparkling. Imereti is the historical heart of Western Georgia and worlds away from Kakheti, the hotter, drier province responsible for the vast majority of the country's wines. Wines are traditionally crafted in tear-dropped shaped clay vessels called qvevri across both regions, but the offerings couldn't be more differently stylistically. 

As for food, think like a Georgian, which is not to say you have to find Georgian food, but adorn the table with a variety of options. I love Carla Capalbo's description of the traditional Georgian meal:
‚ÄúAt a supra, the table is laden with food before anyone sits down. The centre of a long table hosting, say, twenty people will be set with at least seven or eight cold dishes . . . Once everyone is seated and has started eating, other dishes - including hot stews, stuffed breads, dumplings and barbecued meats - begin to arrive and are placed beside (and sometimes even on top of) the first set of foods. If a serving plate is emptied, the dish is not removed but replenished by the attentive hosts.‚Äù 

Bill Jensen, sommelier for Michelin-starred Washington DC restaurant Tail Up Goat, and her sister Reveler's Hour, is a breakout star of the Covid-19 Pandemic with his virtual wine school. In an effort to stay in touch with his regulars and soon-to-be regulars, he launched #StayHome Wine School on March 29th, and continued every Sunday at 4 pm EST for 40 straight weeks. To be added to the newsletter and gain access to the class each week, email your request to: wineschool@tailupgoat.com 

This week's poem was January Flowers at Uplistsikhe by Ana Kalandadze 
 
In Bill's weekly recap email, he said this:
 A heartful "Didi madloba!" to everyone who joined us for yesterday's class! Winemaker Gvantsa Abuladze charmed us all from eight time zones away with our old friend Noel Brockett offering additional commentary from our neck of the woods. Gvantsa (along with her sister Baia and brother Giorgi) makes some of the country's most stunning wines in a style more elegant and easy-drinking than many Westerners have come to expect. It has been inspiring to watch the label evolve since Baia founded it in 2015; to witness Gvantsa become a more prominent part of the brand; to see the range of offerings expand and the wines become more delicious vintage in and out.
 
Like it's signature amber wines, Georgia is a place between - at the intersection of East and West with an economy poised between developing and fully industrialized. Over half the workforce remains employed in agriculture, and the wine sector, albeit ancient, is very much emerging:
 ‚ÄúIn 2018, 245,000 tons of grape were processed by 292 winemaking companies; for a country with a tiny domestic consumption base, that is a lot of wineries. By comparison, La Rioja in Spain has 600 wineries drawing grape from 12,000 growers and 45,000 ha of vineyard, but it is at the heart of an enthusiastic wine-drinking country of 47 million people with huge loyalty to that appellation. [Georgia has a population of 3.7 million people.] The availability of various grants and subsidized loans over the past five years has enticed many urban professionals to mortgage their urban properties and engage in their dream of owning a small winery or vineyard with borrowed money.‚Äù
 
http://www.fao.org/georgia/fao-in-georgia/georgia-at-a-glance/en/ 
 
http://georgiatoday.ge/news/16302/Georgian-Wine-Industry%3A-Implications-of-a-Russian-Embargo 
 
If you want to support Gvantsa directly, just drop her a line through the Baia's Wine website: http://www.baiawine.com/ 
 
- Baia talks about the EU grants that helped her launch the family's business: https://eu4business.eu/success-stories/baia-and-gvantsa-the-winemakers-turning-a-family-tradition-into-a-successful-business 
 
- Food & Wine asks her what it's like to be a woman in an industry historically dominated by men: https://www.foodandwine.com/wine/baia-abuladze-georgian-wine 
 
- Lisa Granik considers the causes and effects of the recent Georgian wine boom:  https://daily.sevenfifty.com/understanding-the-georgian-wine-boom/ 
 
- Wines of Georgia gives you a rundown of the major native grape varietals and geography. 
 Varietals: https://winesgeorgia.com/grape-varieties/ 
Geography: https://winesgeorgia.com/geography/ 
 
If you're looking for an even deeper dive, there are some wonderful resources in print. I recommend Carla Capalbo's Tasting Georgia, Alice Feiring's For the Love of Wine, and Lisa Granik's The Wines of Georgia.
